# =============================================================================
# ECONOMY: THE GUNS AND BUTTER PROBLEM
# =============================================================================

@lbj_econ_inflation
title: The Price of Everything
is-card: true
card-image: img/economy.png
tags: lbj_country_card
view-if: lbj_year >= 1966 and lbj_vietnam >= 30
max-visits: 4
on-arrival: lbj_labor -= 3; lbj_approval -= 2

The inflation numbers are up again.

They are not catastrophically up. They are uncomfortably up — the kind of up that shows up in grocery prices and gas prices and rent prices, the kind of up that working people notice before economists do.

The cause is not mysterious. You are running a war and a domestic expansion simultaneously and you have not raised taxes to pay for either of them at the scale they require. The money has to come from somewhere. It is coming from the purchasing power of the dollar.

William McChesney Martin at the Federal Reserve is looking at you with the expression of a man who has been saying something for two years that you have not wanted to hear.

- @lbj_econ_inflation_fed: Work with the Fed. Let interest rates rise.
- @lbj_econ_inflation_spend: Keep spending. Growth will solve it.
- @lbj_econ_inflation_message: Manage the message. Voluntary price controls.

@lbj_econ_inflation_fed
title: Tight Money
on-arrival: lbj_capital -= 8; lbj_labor -= 5; lbj_approval -= 3; lbj_gs_progress -= 1; lbj_credibility += 3

You let Martin raise rates. The economy slows. Borrowing gets more expensive. Some of the Great Society programs get squeezed because the credit that funded them is now more expensive.

The inflation moderates. This is the correct medicine. It is not popular medicine.

Labor notices the slowdown before anyone else. Meany calls.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_inflation_spend
title: Growth Solves It
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_labor += 3; lbj_approval += 2; lbj_credibility -= 4; lbj_capital -= 5

You push back on Martin. Growth will absorb the inflation. The economy is strong. The fundamentals are sound.

The inflation continues. The fundamentals remain sound. The grocery prices continue to rise.

You are right about the growth and wrong about what follows from it, which is a frustrating position to be in.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_inflation_message
title: Jawboning
on-arrival: lbj_credibility -= 3; lbj_capital -= 3; lbj_approval -= 1

You call the major corporations in. You ask for voluntary price restraint. You call it the right thing to do. You mean it.

The voluntary price restraint is respected in approximately the way that voluntary restraints are always respected, which is variably and temporarily.

The inflation continues at a slightly lower rate, which is something, though not quite what you needed.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

# =============================================================================
# CARD: George Meany
# AFL-CIO. Labor support is real but has limits.
# =============================================================================

@lbj_econ_meany
title: Brother Meany
is-card: true
card-image: img/economy.png
tags: lbj_country_card
max-visits: 4

George Meany has been president of the AFL-CIO since 1955. He is blunt in the manner of a man who has spent his career in rooms where bluntness is respected. He supports you — has supported you — and the support is real and organizational and worth more than most people understand.

He also has demands. He always has demands. This is what it means to have labor's support: the support comes with an account that must be periodically maintained.

Today he wants to talk about the minimum wage. About the right to organize in the South. About what the trade agenda is doing to manufacturing jobs. About whether the war is eating the money that was supposed to go to the cities.

- @lbj_econ_meany_deliver: Deliver something concrete. Keep the account current.
- @lbj_econ_meany_listen: Listen. Acknowledge. Buy time.
- @lbj_econ_meany_trade: The trade agenda is not negotiable. Make the case.

@lbj_econ_meany_deliver
title: Keeping the Account
on-arrival: lbj_labor += 8; lbj_capital -= 12; lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_approval += 2

You give him something he can take back to the membership. Minimum wage increase. Strengthened NLRB enforcement. Something real.

He accepts it with the dignity of a man who expected something and received it.

Labor holds.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_meany_listen
title: Good Meeting
on-arrival: lbj_labor -= 2; lbj_capital -= 3

Good meeting. Productive conversation. You will follow up on the specific items he raised. Your people will be in touch with his people.

He knows what this means. He has been in these meetings for thirty years.

Labor's support softens slightly, in the way of something that has not been fed.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_meany_trade
title: The Long Game
on-arrival: lbj_labor -= 6; lbj_capital -= 4; lbj_credibility += 2; lbj_approval -= 2

You explain that the trade agenda creates jobs over the long term and that the specific disruptions he's worried about can be addressed with adjustment programs. You have numbers. The numbers are real.

He listens to the numbers with the expression of a man hearing about the long term from someone who wants something in the short term.

He leaves without endorsing your position.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

# =============================================================================
# CARD: The Great Society's Price Tag
# The hidden cost — Vietnam eating the domestic agenda.
# =============================================================================

@lbj_econ_squeeze
title: The Arithmetic
is-card: true
card-image: img/economy.png
tags: lbj_country_card
view-if: lbj_vietnam >= 40 and lbj_gs_progress >= 3
max-visits: 3
on-arrival: lbj_capital -= 3; lbj_paranoia += 2

Budget Director Charles Schultze has a chart.

The chart shows two lines. One line is the projected cost of the Great Society programs at full funding. The other line is the projected cost of the war in Vietnam at current escalation levels. The lines cross in fiscal year 1967 and they do not uncross.

Schultze is very careful about how he presents this. He does not say that you cannot do both. He says that doing both at current scales will require either a tax increase, a reduction in one of the two commitments, or an acceptance of structural deficits and the inflation that follows.

He says this is a management problem with known solutions.

You look at the chart for a long time.

- @lbj_econ_squeeze_taxhike: Tax surcharge. Pay for both honestly.
- @lbj_econ_squeeze_cut_war: Reduce the war commitment. The domestic agenda takes priority.
- @lbj_econ_squeeze_cut_gs: Protect the war. Scale back the domestic agenda.
- @lbj_econ_squeeze_defer: Defer the decision. The economy is strong.

@lbj_econ_squeeze_taxhike
title: Honest Arithmetic
on-arrival: lbj_capital += 8; lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_credibility += 5; lbj_approval -= 4; lbj_labor -= 3; lbj_far_right += 3

A ten percent income tax surcharge. It will cover the gap. It will be unpopular. It will be honest.

Congress will fight it. Wilbur Mills will extract concessions. The eventual legislation will be narrower than you want. But the arithmetic will be addressed rather than deferred.

The Great Society survives more or less intact. The war continues. The country pays for both.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_squeeze_cut_war
title: Reorder Priorities
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam -= 10; lbj_antiwar -= 8; lbj_capital += 12; lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_military += 10; lbj_continuity += 4; lbj_liberals += 6; lbj_approval += 3

You reduce the war commitment. Begin winding down the escalation. The domestic agenda gets the resources it was promised.

The Joint Chiefs receive this news with the stillness you have learned to read as something other than acceptance.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_squeeze_cut_gs
title: War First
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress -= 2; lbj_poverty += 10; lbj_liberals -= 10; lbj_labor -= 6; lbj_capital += 8; lbj_approval -= 6

You protect the war spending and reduce the domestic programs.

The things that get cut are real. The programs that don't get funded are real. The people who needed them are real.

You tell yourself it is temporary. You have been telling yourself a version of this for two years.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_econ_squeeze_defer
title: Strong Fundamentals
on-arrival: lbj_credibility -= 4; lbj_capital -= 5; lbj_poverty += 5

The economy is growing. Unemployment is low. These things are true.

The structural problem does not go away because the economy is growing. It becomes a structural problem in a growing economy, which Schultze will point out in six months with an updated chart.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

